{
  "texts": [
    "To characterise an action as cognitive offloading is just to redescribe it in terms of its effects -effects which themselves can be factorised into internal, cognitive and external, non-cognitive components.",
    "I'll now suggest that if HEC's supporters want to resist this argument, they should adopt Anscombe's alternative formulation, \"I do what happens\" as a rival slogan (2000, p. 52, emphasis in original).",
    "By itself, however, this slogan looks to be, in Anscombe's own words, \"extremely paradoxical and obscure\" (p. 53).",
    "The job of this final section is to develop an interpretation of it as a rival to the Davidsonian A-D Principle, allowing us to accommodate the pull towards HEC generated by work on cognitive offloading by adopting an alternative model of action along lines suggested by contemporary opponents of the standard story.",
    "Drawing on this recent scholarship and theorising, I'll present a partial view of Anscombe's complex overall project, setting out the resources it offers for an action theoretically informed HEC."
  ]
}